# Domain Model

## Entity Hierarchy

```
Match (AggregateRoot)
└── SetEntity[]
    └── Game[]
        └── Point[]
```

`Match` is the **only aggregate root**. All mutations go through it.

## Base Classes Pattern

All entities extend `Entity<TProps>` or `AggregateRoot<TProps>`:

```typescript
// ✅ Correct — Props interface + private constructor + factory methods
interface GameProps {
  type: GameType
  noAd: boolean
  points: Point[]
  winner: PointScorer | null
}

export class Game extends Entity<GameProps> {
  private constructor(props: GameProps, id?: string) {
    super(props, id)           // id is auto-generated if omitted
  }

  static create(type: GameType = 'regular', noAd = false): Game {
    return new Game({ type, noAd, points: [], winner: null })
  }

  static restore(id: string, props: Omit<GameProps, 'winner'>): Game {
    return new Game({ ...props, winner: null }, id)
  }

  get type(): GameType { return this.props.type }
  // ... all state exposed via getters
}

// ❌ Wrong — no parameter properties, no public constructors
class Game {
  constructor(public readonly type: GameType) {}
}
```

## Mutable State via Props

Entities mutate their own `props` internally. `props` is `protected readonly` (ref is immutable; contents are mutable):

```typescript
// ✅ Inside entity methods
this.props.winner = 'team1'   // mutate property — OK
this.props.points.push(p)     // mutate array content — OK

// ❌ Never from outside
game.props.winner = 'team1'  // props is protected
```

## Domain Events

Only the **AggregateRoot** (`Match`) emits events. Entities set their own state; `Match` observes and fires events:

```typescript
// In Match.scorePoint():
set.scorePoint(scorer)                                        // delegate
this.addDomainEvent(new PointScoredEvent(...))               // observe + fire
if (game.isFinished) {
  this.addDomainEvent(new GameWonEvent(...))
  if (set.isFinished) {
    this.addDomainEvent(new SetWonEvent(...))
    // ...
  }
}
```

Events are consumed via `match.pullDomainEvents()` which empties the queue.

### Event Class Pattern

Event classes follow the same Props pattern as entities — no parameter properties, `import type` for all type-only imports:

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
import type { DomainEvent } from '../shared/domain-event.interface'
import type { PointScorer } from '../shared/types'

interface GameWonEventProps {
  matchId: string
  winner: PointScorer
  setId: string
  gameId: string
}

export class GameWonEvent implements DomainEvent {
  readonly eventName = 'GameWon'
  readonly occurredAt = new Date()

  private readonly props: GameWonEventProps

  constructor(matchId: string, winner: PointScorer, setId: string, gameId: string) {
    this.props = { matchId, winner, setId, gameId }
  }

  get matchId(): string { return this.props.matchId }
  get winner(): PointScorer { return this.props.winner }
  get setId(): string { return this.props.setId }
  get gameId(): string { return this.props.gameId }
}

// ❌ Wrong — parameter properties + missing import type
import { DomainEvent } from '../shared/domain-event.interface'
import { PointScorer } from '../shared/types'

export class GameWonEvent implements DomainEvent {
  constructor(
    public readonly matchId: string,
    public readonly winner: PointScorer,
  ) {}
}
```

## Value Objects

Value objects follow the same Props pattern — Props interface, class field, constructor assigns, getters expose:

```typescript
// ✅ Correct
interface TeamProps {
  id: string
  name: string
}

export class Team {
  private readonly props: TeamProps

  private constructor(props: TeamProps) {
    this.props = props
  }

  static create(name: string): Team {
    return new Team({ id: crypto.randomUUID(), name })
  }

  static restore(id: string, name: string): Team {
    return new Team({ id, name })
  }

  get id(): string { return this.props.id }
  get name(): string { return this.props.name }
  equals(other: Team): boolean { return this.props.id === other.props.id }
}
```

## Beach Tennis Scoring Rules

### Game — Regular
- Points: `0 → 15 → 30 → 40 → Win`
- At deuce (3-3): need 2 consecutive points to win
- **noAd mode** (beach tennis default): at deuce, next point wins
- Display: `'0' | '15' | '30' | '40' | 'Deuce' | 'Advantage'`

### Game — Tiebreak
- Raw count, first to **7**, win by **2**
- Display: `'0' | '1' | '2' | ...`

### Game — Super Tiebreak
- Raw count, first to **10**, win by **2**

### Set — Standard
- First to **6 games**, win by **2**
- At 5-5: play to 7 (7-5 wins)
- At 6-6: **tiebreak** game decides (score becomes 7-6)

### Set — Super Tiebreak Set
- A single `super-tiebreak` game decides the entire set
- Used for the deciding set when `MatchConfig.finalSetSuperTiebreak = true`

### Match
- **bestOf**: `1 | 3 | 5` (defaults to `3`)
- **noAd**: `true` by default (official beach tennis rule)
- **finalSetSuperTiebreak**: `true` by default
- `setsToWin = Math.ceil(bestOf / 2)`

## Shared Types (`packages/core/src/domain/shared/types.ts`)

```typescript
type PointScorer = 'team1' | 'team2'
type MatchStatus = 'not_started' | 'in_progress' | 'finished'
type GameType = 'regular' | 'tiebreak' | 'super-tiebreak'
```

Always import these from `shared/types`, not from individual entities, to avoid circular deps.

## Use Cases

The application layer lives in `packages/core/src/application/` and follows CQRS. See `application-layer.mdc` for the full guide.

Commands call aggregate methods and return minimal output. Queries map the aggregate to `MatchDto` for the UI. All handlers depend on `IMatchRepository` (a port injected via constructor).
